<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-04-30T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-04-30T17:00:00-05:00" n="611" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d611">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">861.24/1425a: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Standley</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-04-30T18:00:00-04:00">April
                                        30, 1943—6 p.m.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>268. “From Spalding for Burns. It would appear most desirable to
                                ferry as many airplanes as possible via Alaska, in view of the great
                                saving of time in delivery and the difficulties (including effort to
                                disassemble and assemble) of shipping by water. In formulating <pb facs="0770" n="758" xml:id="pg_758"/> plans, it would be very
                                helpful to have information regarding future planned capacity of the
                                route and possibility of expansion.”<note n="94" xml:id="d611fn94">For correspondence on the question of the use of the
                                    Alaska–Siberia route for ferrying airplanes and as an improved
                                    means of communications, see <ref target="#pg_616">pp.
                                        616</ref>–<ref target="#pg_723">723</ref>, <hi rend="italic">passim.</hi>
                                </note>
                            </p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>